This paper deals with information theory and coding, specifically with the capacity-achieving properties of polar codes. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely category. The paper also discusses the construction complexity and decoding complexity of polar codes, which are related to computational complexity, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) another likely category. The paper also mentions the tracking of channel Bhattacharyya parameters, which is related to signal processing, making cs.SI (Signal Processing) a possible category. The paper also discusses the polarization process, which is related to graph theory and combinatorics, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a possible category. Finally, the paper deals with communication channels, making cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) a possible category.
